<p><strong>Registers – LMS Module</strong></p><p>This module will focus on the skills and knowledge required to provide great customer service at the register in a fast and friendly way, in order to deliver an outstanding customer experience. </p><p>After successfully completing this online module, you'll complete practical training on a training register to ensure you can practice and apply the skills. Your manager will complete this with you in store. </p><p>Choose a topic or select <strong>start course</strong> to begin.</p><p><strong>Time to complete: </strong>10 minutes approx.</p><p><strong>Audio/Video: </strong> No</p><p>Last updated: November 2023</p><p><em>Lesson 1 of 5</em></p><p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p><strong>Welcome to registers training. </strong></p><p><strong><br />This training has been designed to give you a fundamental understanding of tasks or situations that may arise when working on the register.  </strong></p><p><strong><br />Let's begin!</strong></p><p><em>Lesson 2 of 5</em></p><p><strong>Getting started</strong></p><p>Let's find out how to set up your register and get ready to have a great shift.</p><p><strong>Set up register area</strong></p><p>Select the tabs below to discover which items you will need to ensure they are in place before opening your register. Once you've set up your register and signed in, you should check your spot balance to ensure you have enough cash to be given as change when required. <br /></p><p><strong>Spot balance </strong></p><p>[Image of what a spot balance looks like]<br /></p><p>Depending on your store, spot balance will be available via the team leader or the cash machine at the start of the day. If you take over from a team member throughout the day, you are required to check your spot balance for the required change. </p><p>As a minimum, your spot balance should contain one roll of each coin and five of each note (except $50 when you will need a maximum of two).</p><p>Check that cash in your register drawer is adequate and presented correctly with sufficient coins and smaller notes to give as change.</p><p>Now that you're set up, signed on and have adequate spot balance, you're ready to start serving customers! The next section will explore different scenarios that may occur over the course of an hour on the registers. Let's take a look...</p><p><em>Lesson 3 of 5</em></p><p><strong>An hour on the registers</strong></p><p>There are many different interactions you could have with a customer when working on the register. Some of them require specific knowledge. You will now learn about some of these key customer interactions.</p><p><strong>9:00-9:10am</strong></p><p>Your first customer has arrived! They are buying various items, as well as a gift card. Check out the process map below to see how you would go through this interaction. If you need a closer look, just click on the image to magnify it.</p><p><img alt="A diagram of a payment method

AI-generated content may be incorrect." src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /></p><p><strong>Note</strong> - Afterpay is now accepted in-store not just online. </p><p><strong>Customer service tip</strong> - Don't forget to thank the customer! "Thank you for shopping at Kmart- have a great day".</p><p><img alt="A close-up of a pair of black rubber buttons

AI-generated content may be incorrect." src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /></p><p>Your next customer is purchasing some activewear that has been tagged for security purposes. You will use an EAS removal device at your register to remove security tags from purchased items. Check with your manager about removing a security tag. </p><p><strong>9:10-9:20am</strong></p><p>Another customer is buying a microwave. This is considered a 'big and bulky item'. Let's look at some safety tips below for handling big and bulky items at the register.</p><p>There are safety tips that you need to be aware of when processing such items:</p><ul><li>do not 'overstretch' across the counter to scan the item</li><li><strong>avoid lifting heavy and bulky items out of a trolley to scan them</strong>. Use the 'Look Up' function on the register. If the product is not available to look up, walk around the counter to scan them</li><li>where a heavy or bulky item needs to be moved, use a two-person or team lift; remember to use the correct moving safely techniques</li><li>while you should not lift any big and bulky product, they should have a weight test to ensure it includes the right product inside. You can assess the weight by going to the product and slightly lifting or sliding the product to judge the weight. If the weight is not right or you feel movement in the box there may be different items in the box!</li></ul><p>Other examples of bulky/heavy items include bikes, furniture and large appliances.</p><p>Your next customer has purchased a range of kitchen items, including knives. In your particular state, the sale of knives is restricted and cannot be sold to minors. Your register flags these items on your screen and prompts you to check ID. The customer produces ID which indicates they are 18 years old. The sale can proceed. To read more about the sale of knives policy and learn about if this is applicable to your location, check out the document below.</p><p>There is a training module on 'Knives Sale in QLD' for all team members who attend registers. Please ensure that you complete this training if you are from Queensland.</p><p><strong>Note: There's also a sales restriction on helium products. For safety reasons, no helium products will be sold to persons under the age of 18.  All helium products will be available for sale In Store only as identification for proof of age will be needed. </strong></p><p><strong>9:20-9:30am</strong></p><p>You've just realised your cash drawer is running low on coins- it's time to order some change.</p><p><br />You'll learn how to do this on your register in the practical activity.</p><p><strong>Loss prevention tip:</strong></p><p><strong>When ordering change or arranging a cash clearance (Code 10), never remove money from the register until the manager in charge of the Customer Service area is present.</strong></p><p><strong>9:30-9:40am</strong></p><p>Your next customer has found the last shirt in their preferred colour and size. It has a small make-up mark on it, so they've asked if they can purchase it at a reduced price. </p><p>You will learn how to do this transaction on your register in the practical activity. </p><p><strong>In situations like this where a discount is requested, remember to always ask your manager to confirm the reduced price of the item, before processing the transaction.</strong></p><p>The next customer is paying for a trolley full of stock with cash. You suspect some of the notes may be counterfeit, so you discreetly contact your manager. Your manager then comes to inspect the note. If they also suspect it is counterfeit, they will store the note in an envelope and report the matter to the police, detailing how they came into possession of it. It is an offence to knowingly accept or possess counterfeit bank notes. </p><p><strong>Safety tip:<br />It is important to note that under no circumstances should you take actions that may jeopardise your safety or that of others. If a customer becomes aggressive as a result of the note being questioned, follow the appropriate steps to deescalate the situation, as outlined in the Threatening Situations training module.</strong></p><p>Always follow the 5Ds when faced with threatening behaviours.</p><p>To learn more about spotting a counterfeit note, check out the document below that is applicable to your location.</p><p><strong>9:40-9:50am</strong></p><p><br />After serving a number of customers, your cash drawer is starting to fill up. To keep you and others safe, Kmart has strict rules regarding the amount of money you keep in your register. Sometimes during a shift, you will need to clear excess cash from your register – this is called <strong>cash clearance</strong>.</p><ul><li>Stores may use either a cash tube, tank safe or cash machine for clearances. </li><li>For your safety and security, clearances must not be counted, but excess cash should be cleared regularly. As a guiding principle, if your drawer gets to approximately ten $50 notes or twenty $20 notes, it’s time to request a clearance. <em>Don’t count, but if in doubt - clear it out!</em></li><li>The difference between a cash and non-cash machine store can be explained by your manager.</li></ul><p>You will learn the steps to arrange a cash clearance, also known as a "Code 10" in the practical activity. </p><p><strong>Note: During busy periods (i.e weekends, Christmas), ensure you perform regular register clearance. Include all $100 notes if applicable.</strong></p><p><strong>9:50-10:00am</strong></p><p>It's quiet now. This is a great time to maintain your register area!<br />Tick off each item in the checklist below, as you read about the ways to maintain a clean, safe and well-merchandised register area.</p><ul><li>Shelves are neat and tidy.</li><li>Merchandise is presented correctly.</li><li>Labels are visible and correctly placed.</li><li>Return customer baskets to designated area.</li><li>Hangers are emptied into large blue hanger bins.</li><li>Nearby food item 'use by' and 'best before' dates are checked (if issues, contact a manager).</li><li>Checkout queuing area is clean, tidy and safe- look for objects on the floor or merchandise dumped in the area.</li><li>Organise with your line manager to return any merchandise abandoned by customers.</li></ul><p><strong>Safety tip</strong></p><p>Ensure the register hanger trays are regularly emptied into the blue hanger bins so they do not overflow onto the ground and cause a trip hazard. </p><p><img alt="A person carrying a blue bin

AI-generated content may be incorrect." src="data:image/jpeg;base64," /></p><p>Push the bin to avoid a shoulder injury. Due to the awkwardness and weight, emptying the blue hanger bin into the cardboard bins “TIC HANGERS ONLY” is a team job and requires 2 team members. Wear cut resistant gloves and get as close to the bin as possible, squat down, and using both hands to support, together lift the bin and tip it into the location. Consider using a <strong>“1, 2, 3, LIFT”</strong> communication method to avoid one person lifting the bin up when the other person is not ready. </p><p><strong>Signing off</strong></p><p>When you've finished your shift, you need to sign off from your register. You should also sign off from your register when you are:</p><ul><li> not serving customers </li><li> maintaining your register area </li><li> leaving your register. </li></ul><p>You will learn to sign off on the register in the practical activity.</p><p><strong>Great work</strong></p><p>You've just learnt about some different scenarios that may occur during an hour on the registers, so you now have a basic understanding of what these processes are. </p><p>You will get an opportunity to practice these steps with your manager, which will solidify your understanding. </p><p>The more experience you gain on the registers, the more these processes and procedures will sink in, but remember your manager and fellow team members are here to help you learn, so we can all grow together- don't be afraid to ask for help when you need it!</p><p>If at any time you're unsure of a process or need more information, you can always speak to your manager.</p><p><em>Lesson 4 of 5</em></p><p><strong>Quiz</strong></p><p>Before finishing this module, let's complete a quiz to check your understanding. </p><p>Pass mark for this quiz is 80% so you’ll need to answer 4 out of 5 questions correctly.</p><p><strong><em>Question</em></strong></p><p><strong>01/05</strong></p><p>Which of the below items do you need to check are at your register before you start serving customers? Remember you can also use the 'look up' function instead of scanning.</p><p><strong><em>Question</em></strong></p><p><strong>05/05</strong></p><p>When ordering change or arranging a cash clearance (Code 10), never remove money from the register until the manager in charge of the Customer Service area is present.</p><ul><li>True <em>(Correctly selected)</em></li><li>False (Correctly unselected)</li></ul><p><strong>Correct</strong></p><p>That's right, when ordering change or arranging a cash clearance (Code 10), never remove money from the register until the manager in charge of the Customer Service area is present.</p><p><em>Lesson 5 of 5</em></p><p><strong>Summary</strong></p><p><strong>Well done!</strong></p><p>You have now gone through the theory behind working on the registers as a team member at Kmart.
